    "last_edit_date" : 1461784112,
    "creation_date" : 1255730831,
    "answer_id" : 1580684,
    "question_id" : 1577014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>As of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mac_OS_X_Snow_Leopard\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Mac&nbsp;OS&nbsp;X&nbsp;v10.6</a> (Snow&nbsp;Leopard), you can run Java 6 in 32-bit mode on either 32-bit or 64-bit <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intel\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Intel</a> processor equipped Macs.</p>\n\n<p>If you cannot upgrade to Snow Leopard, <a href=\"http://landonf.bikemonkey.org/static/soylatte/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\" title=\"Soy Latte\">Soy Latte</a> is a pre-compiled version of Java 6 for Intel 32-bit.  </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 28664,
      "reputation" : 5305,
      "user_id" : 76778,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 79,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e714c804e32e2f8d395421f1ec282ea5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Fgblanch",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/76778/fgblanch"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1461784426,
    "last_edit_date" : 1495541432,
    "creation_date" : 1300108675,
    "answer_id" : 5299077,
    "question_id" : 1577014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I think this other Stack Overflow question could help:</p>\n\n<p><em><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2846573/how-to-get-jdk-1-5-on-mac-osx\">How to get JDK 1.5 on Mac OS X</a></em></p>\n\n<p>It basically says that if you need to compile or execute a Java application with an older version of the JDK (for example 1.4 or 1.5), you can do it using the 1.6 because it is backwards compatible. To do it so you will need to add the parameter <code>-source 1.5</code> and/or <code>-target 1.5</code> in the javac options or in your IDE.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 304259,
      "reputation" : 1661,
      "user_id" : 613660,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aaa58a4e133b8ee09a6fe998e4990ad0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Mark Tye",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/613660/mark-tye"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 44,
    "last_activity_date" : 1498878796,
    "last_edit_date" : 1498878796,
    "creation_date" : 1300470234,
    "answer_id" : 5355841,
    "question_id" : 1577014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In a comment under @Thilo's answer, @mobibob asked how to set JAVA_HOME in your .bash_profile on a Mac. Answer:</p>\n\n<pre><code>export JAVA_HOME=`/usr/libexec/java_home` \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This will dynamically assign to JAVA_HOME the location of the first JDK listed in the \"General\" tab of \"Java Preferences\" utility.</p>\n\n<p>See Apple Technical Q&amp;A 1170: <a href=\"https://developer.apple.com/library/content/qa/qa1170/_index.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://developer.apple.com/library/content/qa/qa1170/_index.html</a></p>\n\n<p>EDIT:</p>\n\n<p>If you prefer parentheses to backticks for command substitution, this also works:</p>\n\n<pre><code>export JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home)\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 748421,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 738753,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/706f08f6ed641071d80b61e755095b92?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Evan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/738753/evan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1304540780,
    "creation_date" : 1304540780,
    "answer_id" : 5889432,
    "question_id" : 1577014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Compiling with -source 1.5 -target 1.5 (in a JDK 6 environment) will honor only language elements that were in 1.5 and prior.  Great.  But there were no language changes in 6 anyway.  Problem with this approach (on Mac with 1.6) is that using classes that came AFTER 1.5 will still compile because they exist in the rt.jar.  So one could run in a 1.5 env and get a class not found exception with no prior warning when compiling.  I found this out the hard way with javax.swing.event.RowSorterEvent/Listener.  Both entered \"Since 1.6\" but are not caught with -source 1.5</p>\n"
  }, {
