    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>JDK is the Java Development Kit (used to develop Java software).</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_virtual_machine\" rel=\"nofollow\">JRE</a> is the Java Runtime Environment (used to run any .jar file 'Java software').</p>\n\n<p>The JDK contains a JRE inside it.</p>\n\n<p>On Windows when you update Java, it updates the JRE automatically.</p>\n\n<p>On Mac you do not have a JRE separated you have it, but inside the JDK, so when you update Java it will update your JRE which is inside your JDK;\nit doesn't install an JDK for you. You need to get it from somewhere else.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 300494,
      "reputation" : 14767,
      "user_id" : 607655,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 81,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/0AnuY.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Meng Lu",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/607655/meng-lu"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1470937501,
    "last_edit_date" : 1470937501,
    "creation_date" : 1400214360,
    "answer_id" : 23692630,
    "question_id" : 1577014,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There are various tricky issues with having multiple versions of Java (Apple's own Java 6 and Oracle JDK 7 or even 8) on one's Mac OS X system, and using different versions for different applications.  I spent some time writing up my experience of <a href=\"http://members.wolfram.com/meng/pages/computing/installing_and_configuring/installing_and_configuring_Java_on_Mac_OS_X/\" rel=\"nofollow\">my experience of installing and configuring various versions of JDK on Mac OS X 10.9.2</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 24885,
        "reputation" : 31372,
        "user_id" : 63550,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 78,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/RIZKi.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Peter Mortensen",
